"Pray continue," said Holmes. "Your narrative promises to be amost interesting one.""You will find it rather disconnected, I fear, and there mayprove to be little relation between the different incidents ofwhich I speak. On the very first day that I was at the CopperBeeches, Mr. Rucastle took me to a small outhouse which standsnear the kitchen door. As we approached it I heard the sharprattling of a chain, and the sound as of a large animal movingabout."'Look in here!' said Mr. Rucastle, showing me a slit between twoplanks. 'Is he not a beauty?'"I looked through and was conscious of two glowing eyes, and of avague figure huddled up in the darkness."'Don't be frightened,' said my employer, laughing at the startwhich I had given. 'It's only Carlo, my mastiff. I call him mine,but really old Toller, my groom, is the only man who can doanything with him. We feed him once a day, and not too much then,so that he is always as keen as mustard. Toller lets him looseevery night, and God help the trespasser whom he lays his fangsupon. For goodness' sake don't you ever on any pretext set yourfoot over the threshold at night, for it's as much as your lifeis worth.'"The warning was no idle one, for two nights later I happened tolook out of my bedroom window about two o'clock in the morning.